comment_message: Few things here whilest i understand that being open is her choice it doesnt quite mix well with buisness, religion, sexuality and political beliefs should all be kept separate from work. She really should have her personal page and a buisness page for prospective clients to see her work and not post anything except work related material on there. I am not a homophobe my oldest daughter is gay and we love her and embrace her with open arms just the same as our others. However being open about it isnt easy people can be terrible and i would tell her the same. Do i think the bride was in the wrong absolutley it was inappropriate to ask such a question however there must have been something on her page that made her ask... i am upset about this i think the bride acted terribly and it shouldnt matter what someone elses sexual preferences are and its even more disgusting that the bride tried to push her to not be who she is. I believe personally to love all equally regardless of theyre sexual choices. Now i also understand that there are people who take issue with others lives and i pitty them because their own lives must suck so much to worry about someone elses like this, but theres no doubt she knew this. So why mix it with buisness just keep it professional ya know?

comment_message: Abigail Davis look I‚Äôm not skinny in anyway shape or form. I can never find a bra any where, pants never fit, and shirts are never the correct size. No ones fat shaming. But my sister and a lot of my family are as skinny as they come and they struggle just as much to find properly fitting clothes. My sister is not seen as more intelligent or worthy because she‚Äôs skinny, she definitely wouldn‚Äôt get more job opportunities, and we are all on the same social status. Honestly the world is changing to hate skinny girls and she gets more hate for her body than I do. So I stand up for her. Her body is real, her struggle is real, she gets no privilege from being skinny. Everyone wants to see a thick girl nowadays, so you should change your mindset about skinny girls. They‚Äôre doing nothing wrong, it‚Äôs just their body that they more than probably hate just like everyone else.

post_text: All hail real bodies!
comment_message: Abigail Davis I would like to chime in that I have had a bit of a fluctuating weight issue over the last few years. I‚Äôve been as low as 130 and as high as 240, when I was in the 130 range I felt the confidence that came with being on the smaller side, I felt the immediate acceptance of all the people around me, the admiring eyes, the ease of shopping, the genuine generosity of others around me. Then I gained weight. When I was at my highest, I felt the immediate judgement, the pain of having to find the right clothes or even clothes that looked halfway decent, people telling me that I was unhealthy even though I was working out and eating right, yet I still wasn‚Äôt enough, and to prove your point even more, when I was on the smaller side I had two job interviews, both jobs I got almost immediately after the interview, I only took one. Then I ended up breaking my leg and had to quit, I gained weight as a result of not being able to move more than a few feet for 4 months. Once I was healed and a bit chubbier I applied for similar jobs related to the field I was already versed in and the moment I walked in that interview I saw the immediate judgement on my appearance. And didn‚Äôt get the jobs (3 that I applied for) now I‚Äôm not saying that my exact weight was the reason I was denied, maybe there was better candidates or someone who had more experience, but nonetheless the judgement was still present. Having something as simple as a mannequin that looks like a larger figure is a great thing to those that have felt the judgement and seen the disgust from absolute strangers who don‚Äôt even know who you are and are basing all their feelings off of the amount of space you take up. There is privilege in being skinny/slim and the privilege is that you will always be viewed as attractive and beautiful and enough/valid. Being bigger sadly comes with the staple that you don‚Äôt always belong and that, guaranteed, you‚Äôll encounter at least one judgemental eye each day you walk out of your house. So yes, having something as simple as a mannequin that has a belly and hip dips means so much more than those that have always seen themselves represented will ever know. Rant over lol.

post_text: All hail real bodies!
comment_message: Savannah Perry Thank you for so eloquently summarizing what thin privilege is and how you have experienced the presence and the lack of it.   There was a point where I worked at a Kirklands, and starting on October 1st I would work wearing a long black broomstick skirt, Black shirt, (required Kirklands Apron), a Black pointed hat that had a sparkle web pattern and was adorned with feathers on the brim, and I completed the look with purple and black striped socks and boots. We sold more Halloween merch than any other store in our district.   I was routinely told by people they liked my hat, my skirt, or other accessories.   I went to town, I did the make up fierce, I did the hair to match. I basically wore a costume to work every day.   A coworker who was thin, donned a wrinkled plain hat, and wore khaki pants and a black shirt and apron. And the entire day I heard people tell her she was a "pretty witch".   People tell me they like my accessories, my clothing, my taste. But they never tell me that they like me.   while thin people are glorified for their appearance and body.   I made the mistake once of sharing a photo of myself on a love your body hashtag.   For 3 months I was harassed with the most disgusting responses and images. The most common one was a photo of a dissection.   All women and people perceived of a s women are harmed by the patriarchy.  And people who are not at what is shown as an ideal weight have an added intersection.   I have not skinny shamed, nor have I have I said that thin people are not real.   Most mannequins do not realistically represent even the thinnest among us. The  clothing is tucked, and nipped, and pinned, and at the smallest size.   And yet I have had a week off people getting in theirr feelings about  this.   Because thin privilege is reall.  It doesn't make thin people  bad for being thin.  It ddoes mean that when thin people discriminate against others, they are doing harm.

post_text: All hail real bodies!
comment_message: I think myself and many others misunderstood your comment. In a post like this, skinny body positivity doesnt need to be acknowledged. They get plenty of attention and inclusion. I think it just rubbed people the wrong way! As for the LGBT plug, it honestly wasnt necessary. I was not insinuating that you are a caucasian marching for equal rights, or that you are straight wanting a parade. They were examples to better explain my point, not a personal attack. I'm sorry so many people are misunderstanding your point,  But honestly? Your comment was kind of negative while your explanation of your comment is super positive. Why didn't you start with the super positivity about how you think its great! Your original comment sounded attention seeking. (No offense)  I will maintain my original opinion. Defending skinny is not necessary on every post about inclusive body positivity. Although people get ostracized for their small bodies, the amount of people that get treated differently as curvier women is astronomical. We hold our body standards to photoshopped ads and barbie manikins. We find flaws because the world around us refuses to allow us to ignore them.   The point of the manikin is that there are not many mannequins that show body parts that women categorize as imperfections. It's even a skinny manikin. It's not plus sized, just honest. There are a lot of comments from smaller individuals trying to turn the attention away from the true representation here. And truth be told, the world is reminded that bodies without those things are real in pretty much any ad and any store around the world. No friendly reminder needed.   Skinny pride and reminders about bodies without imperfection does not belong in a post praising Fenti for acknowledging imperfections in women. Sorry. Mostly because not once in the article did it mention that people who do not have hip dips or stomach fat were not real as you are stating here. They were praising the company for including body styles that no other manikin boasts. Thats what it's about, not the actual size. Not the time to give a friendly reminder that bodies without those are real. The article never insinuated they weren't, and look around, every store around the world is inclusive toward them.   I'm sorry if I upset you, just giving my honest perspective. I just read the tone differently and wish you had included more from your second comment in the original. Either way, the comment wasnt necessary because everywhere we turn, we are reminded that.   The post is literally just a friendly reminder that bodies WITH those things are real and deserve representation.

comment_message: Jennifer Larsen no one was 'offended' by this article other than the few who commented about 'offense'. The article is just mentioning how deeply tied African cultures are to the braiding tradition which is VASTLY different than how other cultures use/need braids. Anytime cases are brought to COURT because of braids, locks and other Afrocentric styles, it is a different experience. Haven't seen any of the mentioned ethnicities be penalized for having braided hair so...there's that.  Anytime in SOUTH AFRICA young Black school girls had to protest just for the right to wear their hair in braids...

post_text: We have been braiding our hair for centuries.
comment_message: Tina Taylor Hehn even then, the rules can get thrown out by someone with an evil racist chip on their shoulders. There was a young man recently here in the U.S. who was humiliated because he had dread locks and was forced to have his hair cut in front of everyone because the ref did not care about his regulation hair cap for a wrestling match. We are constantly persecuted for not just our skin, but also our hair. Little girls in schools around the US have been embarrassed by teachers who 'didn't like' braids or the smell of our hair products, etc. This lasts into adulthood.  Yes, it is truly stupid. A stupidity that has upended every Black persons life at one time or another. Sad.

post_text: Things have gone *very* left.
comment_message: Jen Luvs Reviews did a live stream, including a call with an expert in the industry. No one uses white cotton gloves like that, unless they're working with metals. Hasn't been used in the cosmetics manufacturing labs in decades, they use nitrile or latex free. Jaclyn either lied about her involvement, or she knew the lab wouldn't want to claim responsibility in order to defend themselves, so she threw them under the bus to cover herself and her reputation. Either way, she's lying to get your money.

post_text: Things have gone *very* left.
comment_message: A part of me feels bad for her. But another even bigger part of me feels like she, who claimed to be so hands on, should have seen all these issues first hand before they went out to her customers and put a stop to it. She literally said over and over how involved she was in the entire process. How could she be if there are actual fibers sticking out of the lipsticks?  Raw Beauty Kirsti put up a video of 2 packages she received. One was PR and one was purchased with her own money. The PR package had very little issues and the lipsticks looked, mostly, really nice. The purchased lipsticks looked just awful.  There is no way that wasn't blatantly on purpose. Absolutely disgusting that Jaclyn takes advantage of the people spending their actual money on her crap lipstick. I can forgive the air bubbles. It shouldn't happen but it's not the end of the world. I cannot forgive hairy lipstick. There is absolutely no excuse for it. Jaclyn put up an apology and explanation video recently regarding the fibers and air bubbles but what about the person (at least 1, maybe more) who had literal plastic that cut her lip?!  Inexcusable Jaclyn. This isn't just ripping people off. This is lying about being involved and allowing a lab to use substandard practices and contaminating your product that you sell. Because these lipsticks are CONTAMINATED. If you were as hands on as you say you were then you KNEW about it and didn't care. I have never cancelled a brand before because I've always thought it was stupid. But I will never give you a single penny of my money. You are a liar and you prey on the people who support you. Anything for a buck I guess. Shame on you.

comment_message: I liked it and I appreciated the small changes to the story. But unlike many here I didn‚Äôt like Will Smith as the genie. Although it is hard to do this role after the great Robin Williams, his genie performance felt flat and boring. His singing was horrible and he was unusually dry in the comedy aspect. The genie reminds me of the Joker character. It is a bigger than life character and Jack Nicholson did such an amazing job at it that it would be hard for anyone to have a convincing joker after. However, Heath made it his own and wowed us with his take. I was expecting Will to go deep down and pull off something different, unique and original. I don‚Äôt think he did this at all and for me it was the worst part of the movie

post_text: Did the live-action get it right or nah?
comment_message: Nice article, but I'm getting tired of everyone taking a dump on Ariel. She's more feminist than you think and I'll give you one example. She is the first Disney princess to rescue someone herself and she did it twice! She also loved the human world long before ever meeting Prince Eric which is a deviation from the original Little Mermaid story, where the Little Mermaid's world became the prince and only the prince. Now on to Jasmine, her clothes are beautiful, but the corset on most of them are strange. I would have made everything softer and had patterns on them in gold or silver than just solid colors. The flesh toned midriff on what's supposed to be her iconic teal outfit ruined it. It looks like it will always ride up and stick in her ribs. Either do it in the same color as the rest of the outfit, make it in royal blue to match the peacock theme or do away with it completely since I think that outfit goes under the pink over dress, meaning she's wearing two corsets while going down those stairs. Jasmine in the animated movie was stubborn and did exactly what she wanted and when she wanted to, meaning she wanted to wear all the clothes she wore except for the red slave outfit. Every well-to-do woman in Agrabah probably wore the same kind of clothes like Jasmine's under their robes for going out. Also remember, it was Jasmine's face that Aladdin first saw, not her body. The only person objectifying her was Jafar, who put her in the red slave outfit, and it was Jafar who believed Jasmine's tricks and nobody else. For the Genie, I'm open to seeing Will Smith's version. I don't know about Aladdin. The Sultan and the handmaid look great. Jasmine herself looks gorgeous but so does Jafar, ha!

comment_message: You do not need to wash your legs everyday.  Human skin naturally cleans its self.  Only the sweatiest parts need to be washed with soap regularly.  Now if you were at the gym, ran a marthon, rolled in mud then yes go ahead and soap everything off.  Soap manufactures convinced everyone to over use soap to sell more soap then when our skin dried out they sell us moisturizer.   The same applies to shampoo.  They got everyon to strip their hair of natural oils then sells use conditioners and repair treatments.  Depending on hair type and how much crap you put in your hair you can a week or more before washing your hair.  Oilly hair may need washed every two to three days, but drier wash doesnt need to be washed until it becomes greasy.  If you put oil, mouse, protecting spray, and hair spray daily then wash it, but if you gave it all a rest for several days you will your hair will repair its self and you wont need so much to smooth it out and make it manageable.

post_text: Disney is working to rid itself of one of its most problematic moments.
comment_message: Kristen Leah Dill that's not how racism works. That's not how it works at all.   The part you're not understanding is that your ability to ignore the racial stereotypes and see them as "just cats" who are being jerks is something you can only do because you are white, and you've never had to deal with anti-Asian prejudice or kids at school imitating the cats' accents and butchered grammar in school as a reference to your heritage. If you actually were Asian American, you wouldn't be able to ignore the stereotypes, and comments from people like you would hurt because they deny your pain.  You've had all the racial stereotypes in this song pointed out to you: The gong at the cats' entrance The musical notes that are based on a stereotypical understanding of Chinese music The cats' accents and improper grammar The cats' exaggerated slanted eyes The cats' implication that they were going to invade the house and stay for a while, which mirrored anti-immigrant sentiments.  At this point, if you still don't believe the portrayal is racist, that's because you have chosen to put on the blinders of white privilege.

post_text: Disney is working to rid itself of one of its most problematic moments.
comment_message: As far as the physical characterisrics are concerned, I feel like it was less about race and more about animation 101.  The easiest way to depict someone with ill intent, especially for kids who may not grasp mischief portrayed in song lyrics, is either to give them sharp facial features or a harsh color scheme, depending on the person/animal/severity of ill intent.  Since they're a specific breed of cat, the color scheme wasn't really a possibility, but sharp eyes was.  You see it again with Lucifer, the cat from Cinderella, and most of the Disney villains, none of whom, except in the case of the Huns in Mulan, are Asian.  It could also just be the way Disney animates cats, because several of the full-grown cats and all of the kittens in Dutchess's litter in Aristocats have similar eyes.  As far as the accent given, that was a bad decision.  Flat out.  Bad job, Disney.

post_text: Disney is working to rid itself of one of its most problematic moments.
comment_message: McKayla Brame as an Asian child growing up in the 80s, I found the portrayal of the Siamese cats racist. When I first saw them, I was so excited because I love cats and yay, so cool that there were Asian characters! But then they started talking and acting stereotypical and I was sad and disappointed that I finally got Asian characters, but that they were so terribly done. But I had such a limited list of Asian characters on screen, so it was take it or leave it. :(  Representation matters. Especially when you and your sister are the only Asian kids in your small, Midwest town.  Imagine if it were an Asian movie and the only white character was a caricature of a stupid, oversized, overmuscled white cowboy, who was loud, obnoxious, and super clumsy? And that was the only white person out of at least 10 movies you saw? (I bring up that specific caricature because it's similar to ones I've seen in certain Asian comics I've read, and I find that portrayal offensive too.)

comment_message: What about the thought of leaving these movies in tact, but using them as teachable moments for children? We do a lot of things these days like take down statues and change songs and take away historical objects, but I think it could be cool to leave history as it is, and to explain to children this is what the world was like. Maybe "this was wrong, this was right", explain to them how perceptions and public opinions change. Instead of erasing history, perhaps we could use it to make sure it doesn't happen again, and to help people learn. It makes me nervous to start erasing things we don't like. I understand wanting to be cautious and to not perpetuate inappropriate things. But I think there's some merit to using teachable moments if that makes sense.

comment_message: As far as the physical characterisrics of the cats are concerned, I feel like it was less about race and more about animation 101.  The easiest way to depict someone with ill intent, especially for kids who may not grasp mischief portrayed in song lyrics, is either to give them sharp facial features or a harsh color scheme, depending on the person/animal/severity of ill intent.  Since they're a specific breed of cat, the color scheme wasn't really a possibility, but sharp eyes was.  You see it again with Lucifer, the cat from Cinderella, and most of the Disney villains, none of whom, except in the case of the Huns in Mulan, are Asian.  It could also just be the way Disney animates cats, because several of the full-grown cats and all of the kittens in Dutchess's litter in Aristocats have similar eyes.  As far as the accent given, that was a bad decision.  Flat out.  Bad job, Disney.

post_text: Disney is working to rid itself of one of its most problematic moments.
comment_message: As a Siamese cat owner of 6-7 years, the characters fit what I've dealt with pretty accurately. They're sneaky little shits! I also come from a melting pot family, and tend to be more sensitive with certain issues - being able to see my loved ones be treated like crap because of orientation, race, and beliefs makes you a little more aware (again, in my opinion). That being said, this is just stupid. In my humble opinion, that's part of the story and the legnths at which people go to walk on egg shells when there are things you can do that actually make a difference is ridiculous.

post_text: Disney is working to rid itself of one of its most problematic moments.
comment_message: So the lyrics themselves are not racist but I keep reading comments saying the portrayal of the song is racist. Why is she re-doing the song then? Also, I was raised and have raised my kids the same way, to love everyone, respect everyone and never think yourself better or above anyone else and that is how my kids strive to treat people, regardless of what they see or hear. The hate and evil is everywhere. It saddens me that so many times (not everytime), I hear people complain about racism but equally respond with meanness and hatefulness. And this is what your kids will learn to be like. The love and respect seems to be conditional. People, and I include us Christians, constantly have this attitude of "as long as you love and respect me, I do the same, but if you don't, then I don't." It's called pride. We want to see things change but aren't willing to humble ourselves for the change to happen. We want to receive but not give. Unless we change this, nothing will ever change. Having said that, I saw many people  here respectfully giving their opinions and I applaud you for that.

post_text: This well-intentioned comment can actually be incredibly damaging.
comment_message: Christie Lynn Tondu as a person who have felt fat all her life as long as she can remember, i disagree.

post_text: This well-intentioned comment can actually be incredibly damaging.
comment_message: Julie Johnson I understand where you're coming from(I'm a big girl, always have been), but I was making a point from a scientific perspective, if you will... Fat is a thing you have on your body... I think we all need to explore our feelings when we say or think "I feel fat", and figure out what else we are feeling... Uncomfortable? Bloated? Ashamed? Embarrassed? Sad? Again, from a scientific (and logical) perspective, you really can't feel, or even be, fat, because fat is something you have and not something you are... We need a different way to say it, which is why I said one should explore their other emotions when "feeling fat"...

post_text: This well-intentioned comment can actually be incredibly damaging.
comment_message: I am a thick chick and this article is STUPID!!!! Anytime I have ever felt more fat that normal and made a comment on it, if someone told me I didn't look fat it didn't bother me. Just like in the movie Dumplin, I didn't cringe at that line bc some ppl really don't view you as  a fat person they love, they just see you as someone they love. So for someone to say "you don't look fat", that is not an insult or bad thing. It's just them trying to get you to quit being so hard on yourself. I am fat but getting smaller. I've lost 38lbs. But even at 38lbs heavier I still had a crap load of confidence.
